==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*ligjan-'', from Indo-European ''*legh-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[lidzia]], Old Saxon [[liggian]] (Dutch [[liggen]]), Old High German [[liggen]] (German [[liegen]]), Old Norse [[liggja]] (Swedish [[ligga]]), Gothic [[𐌻𐌹𐌲𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[λεκτρον]], Latin [[lectus]] ‘bed’, Celtic ''*leg-'' (Old Irish [[lige]], Irish [[luighe]]), Slavic ''*ležati'' (Russian [[лежать]]).

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'lɪʤan/}}

===Verb===
'''licgan''' (class V strong)
# to [[lie]], to rest on the ground, to be situated
#:''He læig æt forþsiðe'': he lay at death's door.

